---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const faq = [
  { question: "How do I read a PostgreSQL EXPLAIN ANALYZE output?", answer: "EXPLAIN ANALYZE runs the query and shows the actual execution plan. Key metrics to read: 'Seq Scan' means full table scan — usually needs an index. 'rows' shows estimated vs actual rows (large discrepancy means stale statistics — run ANALYZE). 'cost' shows estimated I/O units (not milliseconds). 'actual time' shows real execution time in milliseconds. 'Buffers: hit' shows pages read from cache vs 'read' from disk. 'Nested Loop' with large row counts often indicates a missing index on the join condition." },
  { question: "When should I use a composite (multi-column) index?", answer: "Use a composite index when your WHERE clause frequently filters on multiple columns together. The column order matters: put the most selective column (highest cardinality) first, or put the equality columns before range columns. A composite index on (user_id, created_at) serves queries like WHERE user_id = 5 AND created_at > '2025-01-01' efficiently. It also serves queries that filter only on user_id (leftmost prefix). It does NOT efficiently serve queries on only created_at — a separate index is needed for that." },
  { question: "What is the difference between a B-tree, Hash, GIN, and GiST index?", answer: "B-tree (default) handles equality, range comparisons (<, >, BETWEEN), and ORDER BY — use for most cases. Hash indexes handle only equality comparisons and are faster for exact matches on high-cardinality columns. GIN (Generalized Inverted Index) is optimal for multi-value types: JSONB, arrays, and full-text search tsvector — use for @>, ?, and @@ operators. GiST (Generalized Search Tree) handles geometric types, range types, and full-text — more flexible than GIN but slower for pure text search. BRIN is for very large tables with naturally ordered data (timestamps on append-only tables)." },
  { question: "Why is my query slow even though it has an index?", answer: "Common reasons an index is not used: (1) Function wrapping the indexed column — WHERE LOWER(email) = ... prevents index use; create a functional index instead. (2) LIKE with leading wildcard — WHERE name LIKE '%john%' can't use a B-tree index; use GIN with pg_trgm for substring search. (3) Implicit type cast — comparing an integer column to a string literal causes a cast that bypasses the index. (4) Low selectivity — if the index would return more than 5-15% of rows, the planner may prefer a seq scan. (5) Stale statistics — run ANALYZE to update planner statistics." },
  { question: "What is pg_stat_statements and how do I use it to find slow queries?", answer: "pg_stat_statements is a PostgreSQL extension that tracks execution statistics for every distinct query. Enable it by adding shared_preload_libraries = 'pg_stat_statements' to postgresql.conf and running CREATE EXTENSION pg_stat_statements. Query it with SELECT query, calls, mean_exec_time, total_exec_time FROM pg_stat_statements ORDER BY mean_exec_time DESC LIMIT 20 to find the slowest queries by average execution time. Reset statistics with SELECT pg_stat_statements_reset() before a performance test." },
  { question: "How do I avoid N+1 query problems in PostgreSQL?", answer: "N+1 occurs when code executes one query to fetch N records, then N additional queries to fetch related data. Fix with JOINs or subqueries that fetch everything in one round trip. For ORM-based apps: use eager loading (Prisma: include, Sequelize: include, ActiveRecord: includes). For complex cases, use lateral joins or JSON aggregation: SELECT u.*, json_agg(o.*) AS orders FROM users u LEFT JOIN orders o ON o.user_id = u.id GROUP BY u.id returns each user with their orders array in a single query." },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="PostgreSQL Query Optimizer — EXPLAIN ANALYZE Guide & Index Strategies"
  description="Complete PostgreSQL optimization guide: reading EXPLAIN ANALYZE, index types (B-tree, GIN, GiST), composite indexes, pg_stat_statements, slow query diagnosis, and N+1 fixes."
  tool="PostgreSQL optimization, EXPLAIN ANALYZE, PostgreSQL indexes, pg_stat_statements, slow query, composite index"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "name": "PostgreSQL Query Optimizer Guide",
    "url": "https://devplaybook.cc/tools/postgresql-query-optimizer",
    "description": "Complete guide to PostgreSQL query optimization: EXPLAIN ANALYZE, indexes, and pg_stat_statements.",
  })} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">PostgreSQL Query Optimizer</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
    Master <strong>EXPLAIN ANALYZE</strong>, choose the right index type, find slow queries with pg_stat_statements, and systematically eliminate bottlenecks in PostgreSQL.
  </p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> EXPLAIN ANALYZE reading</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Index type selection</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> pg_stat_statements</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> N+1 query fixes</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">EXPLAIN ANALYZE — Reading the Output</h2>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4">-- Always use EXPLAIN (ANALYZE, BUFFERS, FORMAT TEXT) for full detail
EXPLAIN (ANALYZE, BUFFERS, FORMAT TEXT)
SELECT u.name, COUNT(o.id) AS order_count
FROM users u
LEFT JOIN orders o ON o.user_id = u.id
WHERE u.created_at &gt; NOW() - INTERVAL '30 days'
GROUP BY u.id
ORDER BY order_count DESC
LIMIT 20;

-- Reading the output:
-- "Seq Scan on users" → full table scan → may need index on created_at
-- "cost=0.00..150.25" → estimated cost units (not ms)
-- "actual time=0.042..12.340" → real ms for first row..all rows
-- "rows=1234 width=64" → estimated rows
-- "actual rows=1289 loops=1" → real rows (compare to estimate)
-- "Buffers: shared hit=45 read=12" → 45 from cache, 12 from disk
-- "Planning Time: 0.5ms" → query planning overhead
-- "Execution Time: 12.8ms" → total execution time</pre>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Index Type Selection Guide</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card">
          <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left">Index Type</th>
          <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left">Best For</th>
          <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left">Operators</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-medium">B-tree (default)</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Most column types, range queries</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs">=, &lt;, &gt;, BETWEEN, LIKE 'abc%'</td></tr>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card/30"><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-medium">Hash</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">High-cardinality equality only</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs">=</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-medium">GIN</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">JSONB, arrays, full-text search</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs">@&gt;, ?, @@, ANY</td></tr>
        <tr class="bg-bg-card/30"><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-medium">GiST</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Geometry, ranges, full-text</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs">&amp;&amp;, @&gt;, &lt;&lt;|</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-medium">BRIN</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Large tables with natural order</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-mono text-xs">=, &lt;, &gt; on ordered data</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Common Index Patterns</h2>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4">-- Partial index (smaller, faster for frequent filter patterns)
CREATE INDEX idx_orders_pending
  ON orders (created_at)
  WHERE status = 'pending';   -- only indexes pending rows

-- Functional / expression index
-- BAD: WHERE LOWER(email) = $1 won't use regular index on email
CREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_users_email_lower
  ON users (LOWER(email));    -- now LOWER(email) queries use this index

-- Composite index — column order matters
-- Serves: WHERE user_id = ? AND created_at &gt; ?
-- Serves: WHERE user_id = ? (leftmost prefix)
-- Does NOT serve: WHERE created_at &gt; ? (skips leftmost column)
CREATE INDEX idx_orders_user_date
  ON orders (user_id, created_at DESC);

-- Covering index (includes extra columns to avoid table lookup)
CREATE INDEX idx_users_email_covering
  ON users (email) INCLUDE (id, name);

-- GIN for JSONB queries
CREATE INDEX idx_products_metadata
  ON products USING GIN (metadata);
-- Enables: WHERE metadata @&gt; '&#123;"category": "electronics"&#125;'

-- Full-text search with pg_trgm (substring/fuzzy search)
CREATE EXTENSION pg_trgm;
CREATE INDEX idx_users_name_trgm
  ON users USING GIN (name gin_trgm_ops);
-- Enables: WHERE name LIKE '%john%'  or ILIKE</pre>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Finding Slow Queries with pg_stat_statements</h2>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4">-- Enable (add to postgresql.conf then restart):
-- shared_preload_libraries = 'pg_stat_statements'
-- pg_stat_statements.track = all

CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pg_stat_statements;

-- Top 10 slowest queries by average execution time
SELECT
  left(query, 100) AS query_snippet,
  calls,
  round(mean_exec_time::numeric, 2) AS avg_ms,
  round(total_exec_time::numeric, 2) AS total_ms,
  rows
FROM pg_stat_statements
ORDER BY mean_exec_time DESC
LIMIT 10;

-- Top 10 by total time (most impactful to optimize)
SELECT
  left(query, 100) AS query_snippet,
  calls,
  round(mean_exec_time::numeric, 2) AS avg_ms,
  round(total_exec_time::numeric / 1000, 2) AS total_sec
FROM pg_stat_statements
ORDER BY total_exec_time DESC
LIMIT 10;

-- Reset stats before a new performance test
SELECT pg_stat_statements_reset();</pre>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">N+1 Query Fix with JSON Aggregation</h2>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4">-- BAD (N+1 pattern): 1 query for users + N queries for orders
-- SELECT * FROM users WHERE active = true;
-- For each user: SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id = $1;

-- GOOD: single query with JSON aggregation
SELECT
  u.id,
  u.name,
  u.email,
  COALESCE(json_agg(
    json_build_object(
      'id', o.id,
      'amount', o.total_amount,
      'created_at', o.created_at
    ) ORDER BY o.created_at DESC
  ) FILTER (WHERE o.id IS NOT NULL), '[]') AS orders
FROM users u
LEFT JOIN orders o ON o.user_id = u.id
WHERE u.active = true
GROUP BY u.id, u.name, u.email;

-- Result: each user row includes a JSON array of their orders
-- One round-trip instead of N+1</pre>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Optimization Checklist</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted space-y-1 mb-4 ml-2">
    <li><strong>Run ANALYZE</strong> after large data changes to update planner statistics</li>
    <li><strong>Check for Seq Scan</strong> on large tables — add index on WHERE and JOIN columns</li>
    <li><strong>Check estimated vs actual rows</strong> — large discrepancy means stale statistics</li>
    <li><strong>Avoid functions on indexed columns</strong> — use functional indexes or rewrite predicates</li>
    <li><strong>Use LIMIT for pagination</strong> — avoid OFFSET on large tables; use keyset pagination instead</li>
    <li><strong>Index foreign keys</strong> — PostgreSQL does not auto-index FK columns; always add them manually</li>
    <li><strong>Use connection pooling</strong> — PgBouncer or RDS Proxy prevents connection overhead from being the bottleneck</li>
  </ul>

  <AdUnit slot="auto" format="auto" label="Advertisement" />
  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
  <ToolPageCta currentTool="PostgreSQL Query Optimizer" relatedTags={['postgresql', 'database', 'sql', 'performance', 'backend']} />
</BaseLayout>
